00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:01.700
- [Voiceover] What I
hope to do in this video

00:00:01.700 --> 00:00:06.700
is get some familiarity with
the graph of tangent of theta.

00:00:08.100 --> 00:00:11.833
And to do that, I'll set
up a little unit circle

00:00:11.833 --> 00:00:13.700
so that we can visualize what the tangent

00:00:13.700 --> 00:00:15.734
of various thetas are.

00:00:15.734 --> 00:00:19.961
Let's say that's a y-axis
and this is my x-axis.

00:00:20.566 --> 00:00:23.701
That is my x-axis, and the unit circle

00:00:23.701 --> 00:00:28.066
would look something like this.

00:00:28.233 --> 00:00:31.146
We already know, this is all a refresher

00:00:31.146 --> 00:00:33.966
of the unit circle
definition of trig functions,

00:00:33.966 --> 00:00:36.900
that if I have an angle, an angle theta,

00:00:36.900 --> 00:00:39.900
where one side is a positive x-axis

00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:42.900
and then the other side,
so this is the other side,

00:00:42.900 --> 00:00:45.700
so the angle is formed like this,

00:00:45.700 --> 00:00:48.166
that where this ray
intersects the unit circle,

00:00:48.166 --> 00:00:49.166
the coordinates of that,

00:00:49.166 --> 00:00:52.033
the x and y coordinates
are the sine of theta.

00:00:52.033 --> 00:00:54.566
Sorry, the x-coordinate
is the cosine of theta.

00:00:54.566 --> 00:00:58.261
It's the cosine of theta, sine of theta.

00:00:58.833 --> 00:01:01.900
The x-coordinate here is cosine theta.

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:04.300
The y-coordinate there
is the sine of theta.

00:01:04.300 --> 00:01:06.500
But we're concerned
about tangent of theta.

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:09.100
We know that tangent of
theta is the same thing

00:01:09.100 --> 00:01:13.666
as the sine of theta
over the cosine of theta.

00:01:14.100 --> 00:01:17.166
Or if you're starting from
the origin and you're going

00:01:17.166 --> 00:01:21.166
and you're taking the value of
essentially the y-coordinate,

00:01:21.166 --> 00:01:23.433
the y-coordinate over the x-coordinate,

00:01:23.433 --> 00:01:25.642
it's essentially the slope of this line.

00:01:25.950 --> 00:01:30.950
This is going to be your
change in y over change in x.

00:01:31.633 --> 00:01:33.833
This right over here is
going to be the slope,

00:01:33.833 --> 00:01:35.300
the slope, I guess you could say,

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:37.700
of this ray right over here.

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:39.900
That's going to help us visualize

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:42.366
what the tangents of different thetas are.

00:01:42.366 --> 00:01:45.033
Let me clean up my unit
circle a little bit

00:01:45.033 --> 00:01:46.766
just so that we can ...

00:01:46.766 --> 00:01:48.100
All right, there we go.

00:01:48.376 --> 00:01:50.667
So now let's make a table.

00:01:50.884 --> 00:01:54.496
So let's make a table.

00:01:56.878 --> 00:01:58.900
So for various thetas, let's think about

00:01:58.900 --> 00:02:01.540
what tangent of theta is going to be,

00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:02.766
tangent of theta.

00:02:02.766 --> 00:02:05.700
So maybe the easiest one,
if theta is zero radians,

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:08.715
so if it's zero radians, what
is the slope of this ray?

00:02:08.715 --> 00:02:10.546
That ray's, the slope is zero.

00:02:10.546 --> 00:02:13.034
As x changes, y doesn't change at all.

00:02:13.311 --> 00:02:14.832
Now let's think about,

00:02:14.832 --> 00:02:16.566
and I'm just going to pick values

00:02:16.566 --> 00:02:18.300
that are very easy for us to think about

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:20.433
what the tangent of those values are,

00:02:20.433 --> 00:02:21.837
and they'll help us form,

00:02:21.837 --> 00:02:23.966
they'll help us think about
the shape of the graph

00:02:23.966 --> 00:02:26.266
of y is equal to tangent of theta.

00:02:26.445 --> 00:02:31.445
So let's take pi over four radians.

00:02:33.833 --> 00:02:37.700
This one right over here,
theta is equal to pi over four.

00:02:37.700 --> 00:02:38.960
Now why is that interesting?

00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:40.554
And sometimes, it's
easier thinking degrees.

00:02:40.554 --> 00:02:42.635
It's a 45-degree angle.

00:02:42.635 --> 00:02:45.833
This here, your x-coordinate
and your y-coordinate

00:02:45.833 --> 00:02:47.044
is the same.

00:02:47.044 --> 00:02:48.833
You might remember, it's
square root of two over two,

00:02:48.833 --> 00:02:49.900
square root of two over two.

00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:51.500
But the important thing is

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:53.033
whatever you move in the x direction,

00:02:53.033 --> 00:02:55.238
you move the same in the y direction.

00:02:55.238 --> 00:02:58.566
So the slope of this ray right over here

00:02:58.566 --> 00:03:00.833
is going to be equal to one,

00:03:00.833 --> 00:03:01.966
or another way of thinking about it,

00:03:01.966 --> 00:03:04.500
tangent of theta is
going to be equal to one.

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:06.433
Or sine of theta over cosine of theta,

00:03:06.433 --> 00:03:07.366
they're the same thing,

00:03:07.366 --> 00:03:09.433
so you're going to get one.

00:03:10.862 --> 00:03:13.032
Let me just clean that up here

00:03:13.032 --> 00:03:16.466
just because I'm going to keep
reusing the same unit circle.

00:03:16.633 --> 00:03:20.996
So if I have theta is pi over four,

00:03:20.996 --> 00:03:24.233
then the tangent of theta
is going to be equal to one.

00:03:24.233 --> 00:03:28.566
Now what if theta is equal
to negative pi over four?

00:03:28.566 --> 00:03:31.733
That is this right over here.

00:03:33.949 --> 00:03:36.866
Let me just draw a little triangle here.

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:39.167
So when x, this x-coordinate over here,

00:03:39.167 --> 00:03:42.300
is square root of two
over two, we know that.

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:44.202
We've seen that multiple
times, square root of two ...

00:03:44.202 --> 00:03:48.161
Actually, let me label
it a little bit better.

00:03:48.161 --> 00:03:50.166
So here, our theta is equal to

00:03:50.166 --> 00:03:52.833
negative pi over four radians.

00:03:53.109 --> 00:03:55.130
Or if you like to think in degrees,

00:03:55.130 --> 00:03:57.766
this would be negative 45 degrees.

00:03:57.766 --> 00:04:01.300
And now, your sine and
cosine of this angle

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:03.633
are going to be the
opposites of each other.

00:04:03.633 --> 00:04:06.500
The cosine is square root of two over two.

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:08.167
The x-coordinate of where this intersects

00:04:08.167 --> 00:04:09.700
is square root of two over two.

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:13.433
The y-coordinate here is
negative square root of two,

00:04:13.433 --> 00:04:17.066
negative square root of two over two.

00:04:17.345 --> 00:04:18.966
So what's the tangent?

00:04:18.966 --> 00:04:21.833
Well, it's going to be
your sine over your cosine,

00:04:21.833 --> 00:04:23.766
which is going to be negative
one, and you see that.

00:04:23.766 --> 00:04:25.433
For however much you
move in the x direction,

00:04:25.433 --> 00:04:27.237
you move the opposite of that.

00:04:27.237 --> 00:04:30.900
You move the negative of
that in the y direction.

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:32.002
Let me clean this up a little bit

00:04:32.002 --> 00:04:35.584
because I want to keep
reusing my unit circle.

00:04:35.900 --> 00:04:38.166
So there you go.

00:04:38.166 --> 00:04:40.900
And so this is going to be negative one.

00:04:41.144 --> 00:04:45.366
This is going to be negative one.

00:04:45.366 --> 00:04:48.350
Actually, let's just start
plotting a few of these points.

00:04:48.442 --> 00:04:51.689
If we assume that this is the theta axis,

00:04:51.689 --> 00:04:53.386
if you can see that,
that's the theta axis,

00:04:53.386 --> 00:04:57.366
and if this is the
y-axis, that's the y-axis,

00:04:57.366 --> 00:05:02.233
we immediately see
tangent of zero is zero.

00:05:02.233 --> 00:05:06.700
Tangent of pi over four is
one, thinking in radians.

00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:10.666
Tangent of negative pi
over four is negative one.

